Good morning,

Big tech earnings start today with Microsoft and Google; alas, they did not=
 come soon enough to avoid talking about Twitter, er, X.

On to the Update:

X
-

From the Wall Street Journal ( https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musk-says-=
twitter-will-change-its-logo-to-x-5f73c349 )

Elon Musk rolled out a new X logo on Twitter after saying its signature blu=
e bird will fly away. Early Monday, the Twitter website started showing the=
 new X logo in its upper-left corner, where Twitter=E2=80=99s blue bird onc=
e perched. Musk had overnight changed his profile photo, as well as that of=
 the official Twitter account, to the new =E2=80=9CX=E2=80=9D logo. The bil=
lionaire owner of Twitter signaled the change was coming in a series of twe=
ets early Sunday, posting that Twitter would soon switch its longtime logo=
=E2=80=94the silhouette of a jovial blue bird=E2=80=94to an =E2=80=9CX.=E2=
=80=9D =E2=80=9CSoon we shall bid adieu to the Twitter brand and, gradually=
, all the birds,=E2=80=9D Musk wrote minutes after midnight ET Sunday.

=E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s an exceptionally rare thing=E2=80=94in life or in bus=
iness=E2=80=94that you get a second chance to make another big impression,=
=E2=80=9D Twitter Chief Executive Linda Yaccarino tweeted Sunday. Yaccarino=
 described X as including audio, video, messaging and banking capabilities.=
 Musk has spoken before about his ambition to use Twitter as the foundation=
 of a vision that he has described as =E2=80=9CX.com=E2=80=9D and an =E2=80=
=9Ceverything app.=E2=80=9D In March Musk said that he thought it was possi=
ble for his company =E2=80=9Cto become the biggest financial institution in=
 the world.=E2=80=9D He has cited as a model WeChat, a popular Chinese app =
that is used for everything from messaging to mobile payments to business s=
ervices.

Twitter=E2=80=99s incoming logo harks back to Musk=E2=80=99s former online =
banking startup, X.com, which later became PayPal after a merger with anoth=
er firm. He tweeted last year that buying Twitter would bring him closer to=
 fulfilling the =E2=80=9Coriginal X.com vision.=E2=80=9D

I have sworn off writing about Twitter multiple times over the last 10 year=
s of Stratechery; the company was what it was: a failed business that punch=
ed far above its weight culturally thanks to its dominance of text-based so=
cial networking, a form that was unappealing to most yet exceptionally addi=
cting to some, including most of the media. Now I guess I get to thank Musk=
 for making that promise permanent, as Twitter =E2=80=94 at least the brand=
 =E2=80=94 is apparently headed for the dustbin.

I don=E2=80=99t, for the record, expect there to be much to write about X e=
ither: the WeChat dream is obviously ridiculous, not because of Musk, but r=
ather the path dependency that undergirds opportunities on the Internet. We=
Chat arose in a country that was digitizing for the first time, almost excl=
usively via the smartphone, which meant no incumbent competition from tradi=
tional websites, banking rails like credit cards, or alternative social net=
works; Twitter/X exists in a particular context that makes the WeChat idea =
inaccessible to anyone, much less a company that has to expend the limited =
resources it still has just to keep the lights on.

Musk=E2=80=99s Motivation
-----------------

Matt Levine asks what exactly Musk thought he was buying at Bloomberg ( htt=
ps://www.bloomberg.com/opinion/articles/2023-07-24/the-apes-can-be-saved ) =
:

I don=E2=80=99t know! I=E2=80=99ll kind of believe the everything app when =
I see it; certainly so far Musk has done a lot to make Twitter less useful =
but nothing, as far as I can see, to make it more useful. Adding payments t=
o Twitter=E2=80=99s messaging capability might be interesting in theory, bu=
t in real life Musk is cutting back that messaging capability, so I dunno.

Musk spent $44 billion to actually acquire Twitter. Then he fired most of t=
he employees, drove away its celebrity users and is now changing its name a=
nd logo=E2=80=A6

If you traveled back in time two years and said =E2=80=9Ctwo years from now=
, Twitter will no longer exist, and you will be able to choose between a Tw=
itter-like service called =E2=80=98X=E2=80=99 run by Elon Musk and a Twitte=
r-like service called =E2=80=98Threads=E2=80=99 run by Facebook, which by t=
he way will be called Meta,=E2=80=9D I=E2=80=99m not sure it=E2=80=99s obvi=
ous that X is the winner there? Facebook/Meta/Mark Zuckerberg have a lot of=
 experience running popular social media platforms, and they employ a lot o=
f people who have built social media platforms (some of them hired from Twi=
tter!), while Musk mostly has experience tweeting (now called x=E2=80=99ing=
???) and employs strikingly few people who have built social media platform=
s, because he fired most of them. There is a certain inertia that causes pe=
ople to stay on Twitter, but if you get rid of Twitter I=E2=80=99m not sure=
 the inertia will fully carry over to X.

I guess my question is, what was he paying for? Musk didn=E2=80=99t want Tw=
itter for its employees (whom he fired) or its code (which he trashes regul=
arly) or its brand (which he abandoned) or its most dedicated users (whom h=
e is working to drive away); he just wanted an entirely different Twitter-l=
ike service. Surely he could have built that for less than $44 billion? Mar=
k Zuckerberg did!

This isn=E2=80=99t quite right: Twitter/X obviously has an incredible netwo=
rk effect; I personally still find it more interesting and compelling than =
Threads, which I=E2=80=99ve argued ( https://stratechery.com/2023/threads-a=
nd-the-social-communications-map/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZC=
I6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJh=
dGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUiLCJhenAiOiJIS0xjUzREd1Nod1AyWURLYmZQV00xIiw=
iZW50Ijp7InVyaSI6WyJodHRwczovL3N0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LmNvbS8yMDIzL3RocmVhZHMtYW5kLX=
RoZS1zb2NpYWwtY29tbXVuaWNhdGlvbnMtbWFwLyJdfSwiZXhwIjoxNjkyODcwMDc2LCJpYXQiO=
jE2OTAyNzgwNzYsImlzcyI6Imh0dHBzOi8vYXBpLnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZS9vYXV0aCIsInNj=
b3BlIjoiZmVlZDpyZWFkIGFydGljbGU6cmVhZCBhc3NldDpyZWFkIGNhdGVnb3J5OnJlYWQgZW5=
0aXRsZW1lbnRzIiwic3ViIjoiUnNldVlFOGpnSGVQcFdKZjFmQWI0QyIsInVzZSI6ImFjY2Vzcy=
J9.la7mTB0JEpy5Cn29dGqB8amB2LhP__u7nJKAx0gEKOd6fW5nH4D1Y7Y7DmbZTmQxRl2opKzw=
GUyAZGo0RzluBs0h750xcXkhWEZTeGzEbw8v11iwOml6gPiFszJPuTBeXKwluPhlKSnUJ3wVF7D=
fkxbcK7n7p7SiZAdR4VCWVqRCLH8iN_64HOFjDVysdg6UQFq9uqppYpZLgDPqC4vnehbBTdCR2b=
MA3sNuxEd6CeTirivu8leX6Osid9kdY5S9XmlfO_fxeSu0LxaXJnB4x7giFS0Twey4xEmcPUoKL=
h-s5xdu5SuTvQqvi9rWIIMlbNiCZRzG2U1w_B2P2aNDLw ) isn=E2=80=99t really compet=
ing with Twitter/X=E2=80=99s core value proposition anyways. That is clearl=
y extremely valuable, even if the best way to monetize it remains as myster=
ious as ever.

To my mind there are two theories that explain Musk=E2=80=99s Twitter stewa=
rdship, and yes, one does paint Musk as a bit of a genius. That particular =
theory is not, I should note, the one favored by Musk fans, who insist that=
 Musk is doing something revolutionary with X, and that the WeChat-ificatio=
n will obviously be successful =E2=80=94 it won=E2=80=99t be. Rather, at so=
me point, one has to wonder whether Musk would do anything different if his=
 goal was to destroy Twitter=E2=80=99s cultural import. Musk killed Twitter=
 advertising, obliterated the value of a blue checkmark, and drove the medi=
a batty as they struggled to reconcile the fact they now hated Musk and als=
o loved Twitter; now they can=E2=80=99t even talk about tweets, but rather =
x=E2=80=99s ( https://twitter.com/elonmusk/status/1683365872323133442 ). He=
ck, even that label, indistinguishable linguistically as it is from =E2=80=
=9Cex=E2=80=9D, seems like a reference to the fact that Twitter, for so lon=
g the primary love of the media, was now a love in the past tense.

I=E2=80=99m not, for the record, ready to fully endorse this theory: it see=
ms too absurd to be true, even if it=E2=80=99s hard to think of what one mo=
tivated by such a goal might do differently, and, of course, there is the m=
atter of that $44 billion Musk spent to acquire the company in the first pl=
ace. Except, of course, Musk didn=E2=80=99t spend that much; he probably pu=
t up around half of that amount, with the rest coming from equity investors=
 and banks =E2=80=94 let=E2=80=99s call it $22 billion.

That is, to be clear, a lot of money =E2=80=94 far more than most of us can=
 even contemplate spending; at the same time, Musk=E2=80=99s current net wo=
rth is somewhere around $230 billion. In other words, Musk is, in the worst=
 case scenario for his finances, out about 10% of his net worth, and hey, 1=
0% to drive the media batty may be worth it to him! Or, to be less generous=
 =E2=80=94 and this is the second theory =E2=80=94 it simply may not be eno=
ugh money to make Twitter/X worth anything more than being a fun playground=
 to try crazy things on the weekend (notice that all of Musk=E2=80=99s pron=
ouncements seem to happen between Thursday and Sunday nights).

This, frankly, is probably the right answer. I have made the case, includin=
g on today=E2=80=99s episodes of Dithering and Sharp Tech, that the same qu=
alities that make Musk a remarkable CEO in physical space =E2=80=94 the wil=
lingness to push to the limits of what is possible, with physics as a natur=
al governor =E2=80=94 make him a terrible software CEO, because there are n=
o limits. But the reality is that for Musk personally it doesn=E2=80=99t ma=
tter much.

Beats and Big Tech
------------------

There was one particular moment in Stratechery=E2=80=99s history I remember=
 vividly: I remember writing very serious analysis about Apple buying Beats=
 ( https://stratechery.com/2014/apple-buying-beats/?access_token=3DeyJhbGci=
OiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ=
9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUiLCJhenAiOiJIS0xjUzREd1Nod=
1AyWURLYmZQV00xIiwiZW50Ijp7InVyaSI6WyJodHRwczovL3N0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LmNvbS8yMDE0=
L2FwcGxlLWJ1eWluZy1iZWF0cy8iXX0sImV4cCI6MTY5Mjg3MDA3NiwiaWF0IjoxNjkwMjc4MDc=
2LCJpc3MiOiJodHRwczovL2FwaS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUvb2F1dGgiLCJzY29wZSI6ImZlZW=
Q6cmVhZCBhcnRpY2xlOnJlYWQgYXNzZXQ6cmVhZCBjYXRlZ29yeTpyZWFkIGVudGl0bGVtZW50c=
yIsInN1YiI6IlJzZXVZRThqZ0hlUHBXSmYxZkFiNEMiLCJ1c2UiOiJhY2Nlc3MifQ.vxOJpZnPa=
oI8mnQKEctUBgE45aTQMEUZ9TY2zlO3TtSdYjZ_-Yw-1kccrp2KdSzdEH499OYDJJ1zjo4xGYTW=
OjAUjMVsCcPL_F5WS34qNQlmT6HVvqe6iYFWDR1KP4fLxeChHs1PDUHGxzb9XFcD03ti1RMgQMH=
2a-8idUdkdAfMKMpvkcriHRf4Uc8OH7hJ_olEnhiGL7YqLME6UupXjO2fX6_9snSabXV3iRSTSi=
htp5SnM5NjqfG4EIanxaPoUN15FwxN-cQkwSJgP6YTsredDHNquHsXHpYFDZXRaGELPAH0Y3zcO=
sjLvn3DDpKUIfHIttyA4Hd4ei-4Yy8F7Q ) ; it was the biggest story of the month=
, and one of Apple=E2=80=99s biggest acquisitions ever, and I was determine=
d to find the meaning in a story that was pretty surprising at the time. A =
few months later, though, I realized that Apple was worth around $500 billi=
on; in that context a $3 billion acquisition just wan=E2=80=99t that big of=
 a deal.

This was, admittedly, sobering given the reality of my job; the Beats acqui=
sition was interesting, and an alluring thing to write about, and it was pr=
obably best for my business if I pretended it was a bigger deal than it was=
. In the fullness of time, though, my belated realization was a fair one: t=
oday Apple is worth $3 trillion and basically none of it has anything to do=
 with Beats.

This, unfortunately, is the reality for much of the tech industry: big tech=
 is big, and everything else is a footnote; it is a credit to the entrepren=
eurs and VCs and employees and executives who continue to work to build the=
 next big thing =E2=80=94 and those of us who write about it =E2=80=94 that=
 the sheer bigness of the most important companies in the space doesn=E2=80=
=99t completely crowd out discussion of everything else, but sometimes a st=
ory like Musk and Twitter/X comes along and we are all faced with the uncom=
fortable reality that a good deal of what we all obsess over just doesn=E2=
=80=99t really matter =E2=80=94 including, apparently, to its new owner.

That is, admittedly, a bit of a dour reaction to this news. I do, for what =
it=E2=80=99s worth, have one positive take: the extent to which Twitter/X i=
s being phased out as a cultural driver, whether intentionally or not, is I=
 think a good thing. Twitter has, in my estimation, had a uniquely negative=
 effect on the world, and I say this as a full-blown Twitter addict who has=
 garnished more value from the service than arguably anyone: not only do I =
use Twitter heavily as a reader, but Stratechery was largely built on top o=
f people sharing links on Twitter.

At the same time, the way in which Twitter both drove groupthink, and worse=
, extremism amongst groups, was a pretty big negative externality. I think =
journalism was invariably in big trouble over the last 15 years because of =
the way that the Internet destroyed its business model; I don=E2=80=99t thi=
nk journalists being on Twitter 24/7 helped, though, both because of the di=
straction but also because of the radicalization and mindmeld that tended t=
o form around every topic in real time and in view of everyone. I personall=
y found it so damaging to my objectiveness and psyche that I stopped active=
ly posting from my main account years ago. I find the already transformed s=
ocial media market, with folks posting on Threads, Mastodon, Bluesky, group=
 chats, etc. healthier =E2=80=94 or maybe that is just wishful thinking aft=
er a pleasant summer day spent playing miniature golf and board games with =
my phone firmly in my pocket.

